WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.860
Welcome to the test set.

00:00:03.860 --> 00:00:08.240
Here we talk with some of the brightest thinkers and tinkerers in statistical analysis, scientific

00:00:08.240 --> 00:00:13.800
computing, and machine learning, digging into what makes them tick, plus the insights, experiments,

00:00:13.800 --> 00:00:16.840
and OMG moments that shape the field.

00:00:16.840 --> 00:00:21.639
In this episode, Hadley Wickham and I sit down with Tristan Handy, CEO of dbt Labs,

00:00:21.639 --> 00:00:26.040
to discuss why SQL, once seen as part of the old world of data, has become central to how

00:00:26.040 --> 00:00:28.320
modern data teams work.

00:00:28.320 --> 00:00:33.520
So basically, roughly a decade ago, a tool in the tidyverse called dbPlyer enabled our

00:00:33.520 --> 00:00:37.759
users to query databases without ever really touching SQL.

00:00:37.759 --> 00:00:43.759
But around the same time, another tool emerged, dbt, and it took almost the opposite approach,

00:00:43.759 --> 00:00:48.279
making it easier to go hands-on and write SQL directly, while bringing in critical ideas

00:00:48.279 --> 00:00:52.880
from software engineering, like version control and automated testing.

00:00:52.880 --> 00:00:58.200
In this conversation, we explore the emergence of tools like dbPlyer and dbt, who they're

00:00:58.200 --> 00:01:01.880
for, and why SQL has ended up at the center of it all.

00:01:01.880 --> 00:01:05.919
All right, hey everybody, welcome to the test set.

00:01:05.919 --> 00:01:12.639
I'm Michael Chow, and I'm joined here by Tristan Handy, CEO of dbt Labs, and my co-host, Hadley

00:01:12.639 --> 00:01:15.879
Wickham, who's chief scientist at Posit.

00:01:15.879 --> 00:01:22.000
Tristan, I'm so excited to have you on, I have to admit, I'm dbt-pilled myself, and

00:01:22.919 --> 00:01:29.000
as a Python R user, I've really battled to explain why I'm obsessed with dbt.

00:01:29.000 --> 00:01:35.879
So I feel like I'm honored to have you here to, I think, really rep dbt and get people

00:01:35.879 --> 00:01:39.879
hyped about what dbt is cooking.

00:01:39.879 --> 00:01:43.480
Hell yeah, I appreciate you having me.

00:01:43.480 --> 00:01:51.000
Yeah, I was wondering, maybe to start out, I know we did a quick demo online of putting

00:01:51.000 --> 00:01:55.400
up a dbt project, and Hadley was there.

00:01:55.400 --> 00:02:01.480
I thought maybe to kick it off, we could just have, maybe Hadley, you could try to explain

00:02:01.480 --> 00:02:05.000
what your sense of dbt is?

00:02:05.000 --> 00:02:10.800
I think the way I think about dbt is it's sort of trying to put SQL on an equal footing

00:02:10.800 --> 00:02:16.520
to other programming languages, i.e. giving you tools for version control, for writing

00:02:16.520 --> 00:02:19.800
reusable functions, or scripts, or whatever you want to, macros, whatever you want to

00:02:19.800 --> 00:02:23.919
call them, like doing documentation and testing.

00:02:23.919 --> 00:02:30.039
That's the thing that seems to resonate most with me, but I'd love to hear how you think

00:02:30.039 --> 00:02:33.160
of it, if that is at all correct.

00:02:33.160 --> 00:02:38.039
Yeah, I think that that's correct.

00:02:38.039 --> 00:02:45.839
So this is fascinating because all of us here are data people, and yet we come from two

00:02:45.960 --> 00:02:50.479
