I, I remember, gosh, this is way back in the day.

00:06:33.160 --> 00:06:36.959
I don't even remember who wrote this, but there was, maybe it was somebody at Stitch

00:06:36.959 --> 00:06:41.880
Fix wrote a blog post about the full stack data scientist.

00:06:41.880 --> 00:06:49.480
And I remember, I remember reading that and being like, oh my gosh, I, I could not disagree

00:06:49.480 --> 00:06:52.640
more with this, this approach.

00:06:52.839 --> 00:06:55.359
But it makes sense in the context that you operate in.

00:06:55.359 --> 00:07:03.519
So like if I think the data scientist is a role that like kind of arose out of experimental

00:07:03.519 --> 00:07:09.760
design and validation, like you wanted to like try to run an experiment on the world.

00:07:09.760 --> 00:07:14.279
And maybe if that experiment had some validity to it, the organization that you worked with

00:07:14.279 --> 00:07:20.239
could, could be, it could, could see like significant upside when whatever the thing

00:07:20.239 --> 00:07:22.200
was that you were trying to prove.

00:07:23.200 --> 00:07:33.359
In the world that I operate in, there are the internal operations of a company and those

00:07:33.359 --> 00:07:40.079
operations just require some data to, to do the things that they do.

00:07:40.079 --> 00:07:45.640
You know, it could be a healthcare provider, it could be like literally anything.

00:07:45.640 --> 00:07:50.160
But you're not, you may be trying to learn something in the process, but you may just

00:07:50.160 --> 00:07:57.799
like need to produce a customer 360 dashboard so sales reps can like do their renewal calls.

00:07:57.799 --> 00:08:03.279
And when you operate in this kind of environment, actually the quote unquote full stack data

