been curated by dbt, but then kind of build from, from there.

00:09:14.840 --> 00:09:23.760
And I think it's also very common that features that get engineered in Python and our notebooks

00:09:23.760 --> 00:09:29.799
can kind of get ported upstream into data pipelines, whether they're built in dbt or

00:09:29.799 --> 00:09:31.000
Airflow or whatever.

00:09:31.000 --> 00:09:32.000
Yeah.

00:09:32.000 --> 00:09:35.640
The other thing that took me like a surprising long, surprising long time to kind of figure

00:09:35.640 --> 00:09:41.119
out is just like getting everyone to agree on like what a metric is, like turns out to

00:09:41.119 --> 00:09:45.880
be like surprisingly complicated because there's all these like little wrinkles that you were

00:09:45.880 --> 00:09:50.239
like when you look at the, at a high level, it's like, it seems pretty obvious, but when

00:09:50.239 --> 00:09:54.599
you start to figure, talk about like, you know, if you just want to know like the number

00:09:54.599 --> 00:09:57.960
of customers, like, like what is a customer?

00:09:57.960 --> 00:09:58.960
Like how do you count that?

00:09:58.960 --> 00:10:04.359
There's like a lot of fine grained decisions in like different parts of the organization

00:10:04.359 --> 00:10:08.000
have like different priorities when they're thinking about what a customer is and just

00:10:08.000 --> 00:10:12.640
getting everyone like, there's some like kind of technological problem or like, let's just

00:10:12.640 --> 00:10:17.880
calculate that number once in one place, but like a much bigger kind of like sociological

00:10:17.880 --> 00:10:20.919
problem of like, how do we get people to actually agree?

00:10:20.919 --> 00:10:24.039
Like what, what is this, what does this number mean?

00:10:24.640 --> 00:10:36.919
Yeah, and the, the thing that I think DBT has done a reasonably good job of over the

00:10:36.919 --> 00:10:43.599
past decade, so first commit to the open source repo was in 20, early 2016, so we're almost

00:10:43.599 --> 00:10:57.640
10 years in, that by and large, there were localized versions of the truth that existed

00:10:57.640 --> 00:11:00.000
at organizations 10 years ago.

00:11:00.000 --> 00:11:06.799
Now some organizations were very good at this kind of thing, you know, famously, you know,

00:11:06.799 --> 00:11:11.119
companies like Facebook and Airbnb and Spotify, like they invested in their kind of global

00:11:11.119 --> 00:11:17.159
data infrastructure, but, but it, and many companies, like versions of the truth were

00:11:17.159 --> 00:11:26.840
much more localized and DBT introduced the idea that you should, you should push these

00:11:26.840 --> 00:11:34.960
versions of the truth kind of centrally and govern them in source control and that rather

00:11:34.960 --> 00:11:42.440
than taking your ball and going home, if you didn't like the centralized version of

00:11:42.440 --> 00:11:50.039
the truth, you would kind of argue it out in, in public and try to come, come to some

00:11:50.039 --> 00:11:51.960
consensus that worked for everybody.

00:11:51.960 --> 00:11:56.280
Now obviously that's imperfect, but, but I think that we've made it honestly like a reasonable

00:11:56.280 --> 00:11:59.559
amount of progress along that continuum.

00:11:59.559 --> 00:12:02.760
It does, yeah, it does feel like that has really changed.

00:12:02.799 --> 00:12:08.599
I think when I was doing my PhD, like 15 years ago, you know, I was working with scientists,

00:12:08.599 --> 00:12:13.200
you work with scientists and their data comes in like every form you can imagine.

00:12:13.200 --> 00:12:18.080
Like it's Excel spreadsheets, it's an API, it's a database, it's CSV files, like whatever.

00:12:18.080 --> 00:12:23.559
And so like absolutely a big part of a role of like a applied statistician or data scientist

00:12:23.559 --> 00:12:29.919
was just to figure out how do you get all that data into like one nice clean representation.

00:12:30.039 --> 00:12:33.880
And I remember kind of thinking at that time, like this, like this, like this is just so

00:12:33.880 --> 00:12:39.479
tough in science, it must be so nice to like work in an industry job where you can just

00:12:39.479 --> 00:12:43.239
like query like the single source of truth and just get it.

00:12:43.239 --> 00:12:48.400
And now that it clearly like was not the case like 15 years ago, but it does feel like we've

00:12:48.400 --> 00:12:54.280
gotten like much, much closer to that now that you can now, like in many organizations

00:12:54.280 --> 00:13:00.400
there's like a decent chance that the data you need is kind of like nicely prepared somewhere.

00:13:00.400 --> 00:13:05.320
I would say one thing that really opened my eyes to DBT that some of this reminds me of

00:13:05.320 --> 00:13:13.960
is that in my big context is I also didn't realize before getting into DBT how capable

00:13:13.960 --> 00:13:19.320
warehouses were of like even unpacking nested data.

00:13:19.320 --> 00:13:25.159
Like for me, that was a big missing piece when people were like, I just use DBT on like

00:13:25.159 --> 00:13:27.479
my raw ingested data.

00:13:27.479 --> 00:13:33.159
Like I couldn't really imagine until I realized that it can like unnest JSON and like pluck

