just gonna say, go have at it. You know how to read Parquet, do whatever. So you need to make

01:03:05.415 --> 01:03:11.894
sure that you give it access to data in the same way that you would give a human employee access to

01:03:11.894 --> 01:03:20.655
certain specific data and not other data. And I think we're just starting to get there in terms

01:03:20.655 --> 01:03:25.775
of how to think about doing that. It's so interesting to think about both from whether

01:03:25.855 --> 01:03:33.814
it's like someone coding in a BI tool or Python and accessing data, or someone even in a spreadsheet

01:03:33.814 --> 01:03:44.575
or firing off a Slack message that then kicks off some kind of research or job. It seems like

01:03:44.575 --> 01:03:52.415
there's a lot of interfaces into this kind of stuff. People have a lot of expectations of agents.

01:03:52.455 --> 01:03:59.094
They think about them as an automated version of a human. Whereas previously, we would have a

01:03:59.094 --> 01:04:05.534
service token, and that service token could control things within one certain application. But an

01:04:05.534 --> 01:04:12.135
agent workflow, now you expect it to interact with four to 10 different tools. And so all of a

01:04:12.135 --> 01:04:19.214
sudden, it's got an auth profile that looks kind of like mine as an employee. You've got to map it

01:04:19.214 --> 01:04:22.694
to a bunch of different applications. So it's not trivial.

01:04:23.135 --> 01:04:31.895
Yeah, yeah, it's a tough one. Hadley, do you have any AI thoughts as we close out predictions? We

01:04:31.895 --> 01:04:35.415
could get a whole round of predictions in here.

01:04:35.934 --> 01:04:40.934
I don't know. It just feels so hard to make predictions right now. I think we're going to see a

01:04:40.934 --> 01:04:45.575
lot of change. Some of it we can anticipate, some of it it's just going to be surprising, like

01:04:46.135 --> 01:04:54.415
second-order effects. To me, when I think about AI, it's all about being nimble, continuing to

01:04:54.415 --> 01:05:00.575
experiment and try stuff out and accepting whatever I believe today might be wrong in six

01:05:00.575 --> 01:05:09.374
months' time. But compared to six months ago, I don't know, I feel more optimistic, I guess. I

01:05:09.374 --> 01:05:14.774
still feel like software engineering is valuable and useful and that there's so many of the

01:05:14.774 --> 01:05:21.575
skills we know still continue to be useful. And now it's starting to think, well, what does this

01:05:21.575 --> 01:05:28.855
mean for data scientists? What are the skills that you need to apply, even though you're maybe no

01:05:28.855 --> 01:05:33.814
longer handwriting all of the code? So I have no spicy predictions.

